- Even if they do a good job...
- No, no.

52:49.166 --> 52:50.376
All those women...

52:50.459 --> 52:51.543
See that sign?

52:51.627 --> 52:55.714
All those names are all hysterectomies
and surgeries and salpingectomies.

52:56.131 --> 52:58.550
It doesn't matter where they're implanted.
They move.

52:58.634 --> 53:01.303
- No, no, they don't.
- They... We have proof.

53:01.720 --> 53:03.722
What happens if there is a complication?

53:03.806 --> 53:08.394
Well, then it goes in the category
of people who have complications.

53:08.477 --> 53:09.937
You remove it, and that's it.

53:10.020 --> 53:11.271
How do you remove it?

53:11.647 --> 53:14.274
You remove it by hysteroscopy.
You put it...

53:14.358 --> 53:16.110
You... you pull it out?

53:16.235 --> 53:19.071
You put an instrument inside,
and you pull it out. You pull.

53:19.154 --> 53:20.572
You cannot do that.

53:20.781 --> 53:21.699
It breaks.

53:23.158 --> 53:24.034
You... you...

53:24.535 --> 53:26.620
You are not a doctor.
You are working...

53:26.704 --> 53:27.913
You are talking like nonsense.

53:27.996 --> 53:30.290
I have 33,000 women
in this group...

53:30.374 --> 53:31.250
No, no, no.

53:31.333 --> 53:32.835
...with over 9,000 surgeries.

53:32.918 --> 53:37.631
I can tell you that we've had fragments
that are unretrieveable.

53:37.715 --> 53:39.049
They cannot get them.

53:42.469 --> 53:43.512
Ah.

53:45.139 --> 53:47.349
Okay, guys, nice to talk to you. Okay?

53:47.641 --> 53:48.559
Good luck.

53:51.228 --> 53:53.689
There's a lot of uncertainty
in medicine.

53:54.314 --> 53:59.111
I think, as physicians, we're not very
good at saying, "We don't know," at times.

53:59.194 --> 54:02.781
It's fine for you
to shout about the benefits

54:02.865 --> 54:05.159
or overstate the benefits of a treatment.

54:05.451 --> 54:07.369
The minute you raise concerns

54:07.453 --> 54:10.372
that something might not be working
as well as it should,

54:10.456 --> 54:13.041
you are often criticized.

54:13.125 --> 54:16.587
You're told
you're unnecessarily scaring patients.

54:17.337 --> 54:22.468
It doesn't seem like doctors
are requiring a high level of evidence

54:22.551 --> 54:25.471
in order to implant a new device.

54:25.554 --> 54:27.806
Yet in order to abandon that device,

54:27.890 --> 54:30.601
they're requiring
a greater level of evidence.

54:30.851 --> 54:34.188
than it took them
to decide to implant the device.

54:34.605 --> 54:36.190
That's turning everything on its head.

54:37.024 --> 54:39.568
We attract good people
in health care,

54:39.860 --> 54:41.904
but there's this tremendous hunger

54:41.987 --> 54:46.533
to have the latest gadgets,
the newest technology,

54:46.617 --> 54:50.120
without the proper evaluation
of that technology.

54:50.871 --> 54:55.292
We shouldn't be surprised
when some of the health care goes wrong.

54:57.461 --> 54:58.587
If I knew this business...

54:59.505 --> 55:01.965
when I got into it X amount of years ago,

55:02.341 --> 55:03.801
I would have done something else.

55:04.635 --> 55:07.596
I worked for one of the largest
medical device companies in the world.

55:07.679 --> 55:12.142
My ultimate job was to make sure that
the surgeons used my implants in surgery.

55:12.643 --> 55:13.727
It's all about usage.

55:14.728 --> 55:18.023
So the more implants you use,
the more money they're going to make.

55:18.106 --> 55:20.275
It's gotten worse over time
because of greed.

55:20.359 --> 55:24.446
Most doctors do the right thing and
always will to the best of their ability.

55:24.530 --> 55:29.201
But some fraction of doctors
respond to the perverse incentives

55:29.284 --> 55:32.246
of getting paid more for the more you do,

55:32.329 --> 55:36.291
regardless of the appropriateness
of that medical care.

55:36.917 --> 55:41.797
There are kickbacks in the United States
today that are entirely legal.

55:41.880 --> 55:45.634
It doesn't have to necessarily be,
"Dr. Jones, I'm giving you money."

55:45.717 --> 55:47.928
It could be consulting,
it could be teaching.

55:48.512 --> 55:50.889
It could be providing money
for a fellowship program.

55:57.688 --> 56:00.649
There's some doctors that are good,
some doctors that aren't.

56:00.899 --> 56:02.943
I had one surgeon recently who said,

56:03.026 --> 56:06.071
"You make the best products,
but you don't do enough for me,

56:06.613 --> 56:08.991
so I'm using somebody else
because they do more for me."

56:10.033 --> 56:11.326
Welcome to the business.

56:16.456 --> 56:20.127
<i>In days gone by,
surgery was all about blood and guts.</i>

56:21.128 --> 56:24.381
<i>In the future,
surgery will be about bits and bytes.</i>

56:25.507 --> 56:27.467
<i>Is the future already here?</i>

56:29.011 --> 56:31.763
<i>It's a blend of science fiction
and medical reality.</i>

56:33.932 --> 56:35.851
<i>The robot will see you now.</i>

56:37.811 --> 56:39.771
<i>Tonight, a story
from the cutting edge.</i>

56:39.855 --> 56:42.024
<i>The million-dollar Da Vinci system,</i>

56:42.107 --> 56:45.110
<i>a revolutionary tool
for surgeries of all kinds.</i>

56:45.193 --> 56:48.530
<i>The Da Vinci is a large,
fairly complicated robot</i>

56:48.614 --> 56:54.536
<i>able to bring a camera and instruments
in together through one small tube.</i>

56:55.078 --> 56:57.122
<i>The Da Vinci is able to reach anywhere</i>

56:57.998 --> 57:00.667
<i>Very exciting to think
where we get to go with this.</i>

57:01.919 --> 57:04.630
Da Vinci allows us
to do remote surgery

57:04.713 --> 57:06.965
from about seven feet away
from the patient.

57:07.549 --> 57:11.595
We work in a remote control console,
sort of like a video game machine.

57:11.720 --> 57:15.015
We look on the screen,
at the image from inside the abdomen.

57:15.515 --> 57:19.144
And we can perform the operation
with remote control hands.

57:19.728 --> 57:24.816
<i>Da Vinci, by Intuitive Surgical.
They're now in 64 countries.</i>

57:24.900 --> 57:28.695
<i>Intuitive is absolutely
the dominant market leader in this field</i>

57:28.779 --> 57:31.698
<i>with a turnover last year
of over $2 billion.</i>

57:31.782 --> 57:33.784
We're an innovative company.

57:33.867 --> 57:36.203
We will continue to innovate,
put new products out.

57:36.286 --> 57:40.624
Intuitive is motivated by the opportunity
to invent new things, create the future.

57:40.707 --> 57:43.669
<i>That is my vision for your future.</i>

57:44.461 --> 57:46.004
<i>Thank you.</i>

57:54.304 --> 57:57.849
The story of how the robot
came into health care

57:57.933 --> 58:02.145
is the story of what's wrong with medicine
in America today.

58:02.646 --> 58:07.567
Massive adoption of a new technology
with little evaluation of the outcomes.

58:17.828 --> 58:21.373
The Da Vinci robot
was marketed with a strategy

58:21.456 --> 58:23.667
of approaching doctors and communities

58:23.750 --> 58:28.171
and telling those doctors,
"We can help drive business to you.

58:29.589 --> 58:32.384
We can market you as the robot doctor."

58:38.181 --> 58:41.101
The robot is better
for certain operations.

58:41.643 --> 58:45.564
But in many situations,
it provides no benefit to the patient,

58:45.647 --> 58:49.818
and it may add operation time
and it may add some risks.

58:52.029 --> 58:53.780
<i>"You need surgery."</i>

58:54.281 --> 58:56.366
<i>Three words no one wants to hear.</i>

58:56.616 --> 59:00.787
<i>This video will explain your surgical
options for a hysterectomy...</i>

59:01.329 --> 59:06.585
Hysterectomies are a very high-volume,
common procedure in the US.

59:06.668 --> 59:11.131
About 500,000 women
have their uterus removed every year.

59:11.882 --> 59:16.219
<i>During a hysterectomy,
doctors remove part or all of the uterus,</i>

59:16.303 --> 59:20.265
<i>the cervix, both fallopian tubes,
and both ovaries.</i>

59:21.558 --> 59:24.895
<i>The surgeon then stitches
the internal opening closed.</i>

59:25.520 --> 59:27.606
<i>If you're told you need a hysterectomy...</i>

59:28.231 --> 59:30.609
<i>ask your doctor about Da Vinci surgery.</i>

59:33.195 --> 59:34.863
I had a biopsy,

59:34.946 --> 59:38.950
and it came back positive
for, um, endometrial cancer.

59:39.409 --> 59:43.246
I was having a lot of female trouble,
a lot of ovarian cysts.

59:43.330 --> 59:45.624
They sent me for a vaginal ultrasound

59:45.874 --> 59:48.835
because we couldn't figure out
why my blood counts were so low,

59:48.919 --> 59:50.545
and I had a tumor.

59:51.004 --> 59:53.799
I was diagnosed with uterine cancer.

59:53.882 --> 59:55.967
I actually was kind of happy,

59:56.051 --> 59:58.762
because I said,
if I have to have cancer anywhere,

59:58.845 --> 01:00:02.516
that's the place to have it,
because I can have it taken out.

01:00:02.766 --> 01:00:05.227
The doctor recommended a hysterectomy.

01:00:05.310 --> 01:00:11.066
And the only type that he said he did
was the Da Vinci.

01:00:11.149 --> 01:00:16.571
He said, "Well the best way to do this,
the fastest way and the quickest recovery

01:00:16.655 --> 01:00:19.282
would be to use the Da Vinci robot."

01:00:19.366 --> 01:00:22.661
It just sounded like the newest,
greatest thing,

01:00:22.786 --> 01:00:25.580
and I had no reason to believe otherwise.

01:00:39.636 --> 01:00:43.265
Originally,
Intuitive Surgical told the FDA

01:00:43.348 --> 01:00:46.518
that a huge amount of training
would be provided

01:00:46.601 --> 01:00:49.521
as part of the sale of the machine
to the hospitals,

01:00:49.604 --> 01:00:53.275
but shortly after
the FDA gave permission to market,

01:00:53.358 --> 01:00:57.571
Intuitive scaled back
all of the training requirements.

01:00:58.155 --> 01:01:01.658
And the reason is,
if they said, "Your surgeons can use it,

01:01:01.741 --> 01:01:05.996
but they need nine weeks of training,"
no one's gonna buy the machine.

01:01:06.621 --> 01:01:09.958
So you have surgeons who

01:01:10.041 --> 01:01:16.089
operate for half a day on pigs,
take a ten-question multiple-choice test,

01:01:16.173 --> 01:01:20.719
and have a proctor, another surgeon,
watch them do two surgeries,

01:01:20.802 --> 01:01:22.971
then they're turned loose
with the machine.

01:01:23.597 --> 01:01:28.059
I was told that it takes ten cases
to get good at robotics.

01:01:28.768 --> 01:01:30.937
But I know now, in retrospect,

01:01:31.021 --> 01:01:33.773
that I didn't really start
to feel comfortable

01:01:34.191 --> 01:01:36.568
until I was about 200 or 300 cases.

01:01:37.444 --> 01:01:40.864
In other words, that area
where you'd call yourself proficient.

01:01:41.489 --> 01:01:45.076
The surgical robot in inexperienced hands

01:01:45.160 --> 01:01:49.581
adds complication or injury rates
to the patient.

01:01:50.290 --> 01:01:54.544
A lot of surgeons
that shouldn't be using it are using it.

01:01:55.212 --> 01:01:56.338
That's the problem.

01:01:58.506 --> 01:02:02.052
So I had the hysterectomy, go home.

01:02:03.220 --> 01:02:05.680
I'm thinking, "Wow, This is smooth, easy."

01:02:05.764 --> 01:02:08.767
Within a day or two,
I was running up and down the stairs.

01:02:09.351 --> 01:02:13.146
And then a couple of weeks later,

01:02:13.230 --> 01:02:15.565
I started to not feel so great.

01:02:17.150 --> 01:02:20.862
I was getting up in the morning,
I sat down to go to the bathroom,

01:02:20.946 --> 01:02:22.906
I felt all this pressure.

01:02:23.240 --> 01:02:24.532
I looked down

01:02:24.616 --> 01:02:26.243
and this huge...

01:02:27.160 --> 01:02:31.414
pomegranate-looking thing
was protruding from my legs.

01:02:31.498 --> 01:02:35.335
I think I was actually at my clothesline,
putting something...

01:02:35.418 --> 01:02:38.838
I think I'd washed a load of sheets,
and I heard a pop.

01:02:38.922 --> 01:02:42.550
I go to the restroom
and I feel something emerge

01:02:42.634 --> 01:02:44.469
from my vagina.

01:02:44.552 --> 01:02:46.596
A whoosh of liquid came out.

01:02:47.472 --> 01:02:52.602
And now there was about three inches
of my insides coming out of me.

01:02:52.686 --> 01:02:54.479
I thought I was gonna throw up.

01:02:55.313 --> 01:02:57.148
And when I did, I heaved...

01:02:57.941 --> 01:03:01.528
and my intestines came down
like halfway to my knees.

01:03:01.611 --> 01:03:03.697
I had three feet of my colon fall out.

01:03:04.531 --> 01:03:07.158
It's in the documentation. So...

01:03:07.242 --> 01:03:08.285
I get a towel...

01:03:09.619 --> 01:03:10.620
and hold it in.

01:03:10.704 --> 01:03:14.291
I run in there, fall out on the floor,
and my husband's like, "What's wrong?"

01:03:14.374 --> 01:03:17.085
I said, "My colon's fallen out."
He said, "Let me see."

01:03:17.168 --> 01:03:21.214
He saw and then he totally
had a nervous breakdown.

01:03:31.016 --> 01:03:34.602
Then, when I got to the hospital,
they didn't know what to do.

01:03:34.686 --> 01:03:36.646
They were freaking out.
They'd never seen it.

01:03:36.730 --> 01:03:39.733
I get to the emergency room,

01:03:39.816 --> 01:03:44.279
and I remember thinking so clearly
that I was dead, like this was it.

01:03:44.362 --> 01:03:47.699
They had to call the specialist,

01:03:47.782 --> 01:03:50.577
and he said,
"I don't even know if the surgery...

01:03:50.660 --> 01:03:51.870
I can't say if it'll...

01:03:52.746 --> 01:03:54.581
save her now. I'll do my best."

01:03:55.832 --> 01:03:57.834
I have nightmares about it all the time

01:03:57.917 --> 01:04:01.713
where I think I'm on that table,
going into the operating room.

01:04:02.297 --> 01:04:04.716
You know, just terrible,
terrible memories of it,

01:04:04.799 --> 01:04:07.218
and it just never seems to leave me.

01:04:07.302 --> 01:04:08.136
It's been...

01:04:09.554 --> 01:04:11.181
what, three years?

01:04:13.516 --> 01:04:15.685
And I still have... problems.

01:04:16.227 --> 01:04:20.982
I have had to give up a dream
of ever having a partner,

01:04:21.066 --> 01:04:23.276
of ever being intimate again,

01:04:23.360 --> 01:04:25.362
because, to me, um...

01:04:26.071 --> 01:04:28.156
penetration means death.

01:04:28.948 --> 01:04:30.575
It changed the full direction...

01:04:31.743 --> 01:04:32.619
of my life.

01:04:33.244 --> 01:04:35.080
It's taken my life away.

01:04:35.163 --> 01:04:37.707
I'm sorry I ever heard
the word Da Vinci.

01:04:37.791 --> 01:04:40.085
And then, like I said,
every time that I...

01:04:41.252 --> 01:04:46.091
hear of more injuries,
it just rubs salt in the wound.

01:05:08.863 --> 01:05:10.031
Car wash!

01:05:13.535 --> 01:05:16.287
After three years of bleeding,

01:05:16.371 --> 01:05:18.123
I ended up having a hysterectomy.

01:05:18.748 --> 01:05:21.668
And no more bleeding,
but the pain is still severe.

01:05:22.544 --> 01:05:25.922
The pain that I had sometimes prevented me
from going to work.

01:05:27.132 --> 01:05:29.801
And eventually, I lost my job.

01:05:31.302 --> 01:05:35.056
I had to do this car wash
because I haven't worked for a month.

01:05:35.932 --> 01:05:37.851
My doctor just put me on disability...

01:05:38.518 --> 01:05:39.894
which could take months.

01:05:40.645 --> 01:05:42.689
So I'm out of income right now.

01:05:43.314 --> 01:05:45.191
- Oh, thank you so much.
- That'll help you out.

01:05:45.275 --> 01:05:47.444
- Thank you. May God bless you.
- Okay.

01:05:48.069 --> 01:05:49.821
I can't afford my rent right now.

01:05:50.530 --> 01:05:51.906
So I have to move out,

01:05:51.990 --> 01:05:55.785
and if I don't find a place,
and without income and proof of income,

01:05:55.869 --> 01:05:57.829
I can't get an apartment or anything,

01:05:57.912 --> 01:06:00.290
so I'm scared I'm gonna have to be split
with my kids.

01:06:06.212 --> 01:06:07.964
Ever since 2011...

01:06:08.631 --> 01:06:10.216
we've moved around a lot.

01:06:12.427 --> 01:06:15.472
I don't think we've had one place
that was stable.

01:06:16.306 --> 01:06:17.223
Ever.

01:06:17.724 --> 01:06:20.101
We don't know
where we're going to be at school.

01:06:21.603 --> 01:06:24.189
Because we're gonna get another house,

01:06:24.272 --> 01:06:26.649
and I don't know
where that house is gonna be.

01:06:27.942 --> 01:06:31.488
My mom can't keep a job
because she has to go to the doctors a lot

01:06:31.571 --> 01:06:34.449
'cause she gets sick a lot,
and it's just...

01:06:35.116 --> 01:06:37.994
It ruins her opportunity of having a job.

01:06:39.537 --> 01:06:42.332
It makes me feel sad
that my mom is at the hospital.

01:07:16.824 --> 01:07:19.702
It's tough,
watching her not be able to do stuff.

01:07:20.828 --> 01:07:22.705
That much more I have to do.

01:07:23.039 --> 01:07:24.374
We used to do it together.

01:07:26.251 --> 01:07:30.713
I suck now. I'm just cranky and miserable,
in pain all the time.

01:07:30.797 --> 01:07:32.715
I'm not fun.

01:07:32.799 --> 01:07:36.803
I can't drink, I can't dance,
I can't do anything.

01:07:40.181 --> 01:07:41.224
Well...

01:07:41.307 --> 01:07:43.393
But at the same time...

01:07:44.435 --> 01:07:47.522
You know,
I'm so grateful for what we have.

01:07:47.605 --> 01:07:49.065
We have great kids

01:07:49.482 --> 01:07:52.569
and a great house
and we have each other and...

01:07:53.319 --> 01:07:55.029
we're alive.

01:07:56.072 --> 01:07:57.907
How does it affect your love life?

01:07:58.575 --> 01:08:00.743
Oh... Oh, God.

01:08:00.827 --> 01:08:03.037
- It was terrible for a while.
- Yeah.

01:08:03.746 --> 01:08:05.623
- There was no love life.
- No.

01:08:06.207 --> 01:08:07.875
- When I...
- With all the surgeries and stuff.

01:08:07.959 --> 01:08:10.378
But even when I first had it in,
it was painful.

01:08:10.461 --> 01:08:11.296
Yeah.

01:08:11.921 --> 01:08:14.716
That part of our life
has been ruined permanently.

01:08:16.175 --> 01:08:17.010
It's hard.

01:08:17.093 --> 01:08:19.636
Yeah, you don't...
I don't think it ever goes away.

01:08:19.720 --> 01:08:21.221
I don't think it ever will.

01:08:21.848 --> 01:08:26.352
It's sad because I have seen other
people's relationships die in the group.

01:08:26.435 --> 01:08:29.229
I've seen a lot of women
whose husbands have walked out

01:08:29.314 --> 01:08:31.064
- over the intimacy...
- Lots.

01:08:31.149 --> 01:08:32.567
...the lack of intimacy.

01:08:33.192 --> 01:08:38.363
I've seen women suicidal,
women losing their families and...

01:08:39.782 --> 01:08:42.452
thinking that there's no reason
to stay alive.

01:08:48.916 --> 01:08:51.044
I think it's amazing what she's done...

01:08:51.586 --> 01:08:52.754
to help these women.

01:08:54.671 --> 01:08:57.550
Facebook is a full-time job for her now,
basically.

01:08:57.634 --> 01:08:59.135
She wakes up in the morning...

01:08:59.218 --> 01:09:00.803
She's a very determined person.

01:09:00.886 --> 01:09:03.514
She gets something in her head,
and that's it.

01:09:17.236 --> 01:09:21.240
I started getting random messages
in my Facebook...

01:09:22.450 --> 01:09:27.497
from women who started connecting me
with the Gabriella Avina

01:09:27.580 --> 01:09:30.375
that was the spokesperson,
the <i>Ask Gaby.</i>

01:09:30.750 --> 01:09:31.709
They found me...

01:09:32.542 --> 01:09:36.089
and said, "Are you the Gaby
that was speaking for Essure?

01:09:36.171 --> 01:09:37.298
Will you talk to us?"

01:09:38.299 --> 01:09:39.300
And finally...

01:09:39.801 --> 01:09:42.470
uh,
probably about a year of them trying...

01:09:43.136 --> 01:09:46.849
one of them said,
"Can you just tell me how your health is?"

01:09:48.142 --> 01:09:49.394
And then I listened.

01:09:51.145 --> 01:09:52.897
I was fatigued.

01:09:52.979 --> 01:09:54.315
I was tired all the time.

01:09:55.149 --> 01:09:56.484
Then I started falling.

01:09:57.026 --> 01:09:58.986
Just... My legs would give out.

01:09:59.237 --> 01:10:03.241
The doctor said
it was an immune response to something.

01:10:04.450 --> 01:10:07.870
My story was similar to so many others.

01:10:09.247 --> 01:10:10.790
All of a sudden,

01:10:10.873 --> 01:10:12.083
it all made sense.

01:10:14.127 --> 01:10:17.880
If only they'd been honest with me
from the very, very beginning.

01:10:17.964 --> 01:10:21.092
<i>The Essure procedure
can be performed in your doctor's office</i>

01:10:21.175 --> 01:10:23.094
<i>and is over 99% effective.</i>

01:10:23.177 --> 01:10:25.763
<i>It's 99.74% effective.</i>

01:10:25.847 --> 01:10:28.474
<i>It's 99.8% effective.</i>

01:10:28.558 --> 01:10:31.686
<i>It's over 99.95% effective.</i>

01:10:32.520 --> 01:10:35.481
It really wasn't tested
for a sufficient amount of time.

01:10:35.565 --> 01:10:40.903
Most patients that had the Essure device
were followed for about 12-18 months,

01:10:40.987 --> 01:10:46.659
and the manufacturer reported
very satisfactory results from it.

01:10:46.743 --> 01:10:50.663
But for a product that's supposed to be
a lifetime implant,

01:10:50.747 --> 01:10:54.625
to cut off the study window
at about a year and a half

01:10:54.709 --> 01:10:56.836
left a lot of questions unanswered.

01:10:58.004 --> 01:10:59.964
I was part of the clinical trial

01:11:00.339 --> 01:11:03.259
and no one asked me,
"Are you feeling sick?

01:11:03.342 --> 01:11:04.802
What is your health like?"

01:11:04.886 --> 01:11:08.139
<i>Almost all women
who participated in the clinical studies</i>

01:11:08.222 --> 01:11:13.895
<i>rated their satisfaction with Essure
as good, very good or excellent.</i>

01:11:14.812 --> 01:11:19.150
The first time I saw the question,
"Rate your comfort of wearing the device,"

01:11:19.233 --> 01:11:21.360
I said, "What does this mean?

01:11:21.444 --> 01:11:22.779
I'm not wearing anything.

01:11:22.862 --> 01:11:25.364
This is something
that's implanted inside of my body."

01:11:25.740 --> 01:11:27.950
The nurse said, "Can you feel it?"

01:11:28.618 --> 01:11:31.913
I said, "I can feel pain in my abdomen.

01:11:31.996 --> 01:11:35.333
Where that pain is coming from,
I don't know."

01:11:35.708 --> 01:11:38.002
And she said,
"Then rate it as excellent."

01:11:38.628 --> 01:11:40.588
They would say,
"Are you happy with the product?"

01:11:41.214 --> 01:11:45.551
I would say, "No," and they would say,
"But you're not pregnant?"

01:11:46.135 --> 01:11:47.345
I would say, "Correct."

01:11:47.929 --> 01:11:51.015
"Then it's doing its job,
so you have to be happy with that."

01:11:52.642 --> 01:11:56.562
The most striking thing is they'd
crossed out answers and changed them

01:11:56.646 --> 01:11:58.689
Where it said I was having pain,

01:11:58.815 --> 01:12:02.068
they'd crossed it off
and said, "No pain reported."

01:12:02.819 --> 01:12:05.071
When I questioned Bayer about it,

01:12:05.154 --> 01:12:08.449
they said this is absolutely customary
in a clinical trial.

01:12:19.919 --> 01:12:21.003
It turns out

01:12:21.087 --> 01:12:24.757
that the vast majority of research
is not coming from an objective source.

01:12:25.424 --> 01:12:29.887
It used to be
that about 70% of biomedical research

01:12:29.971 --> 01:12:31.472
was funded by the government.

01:12:31.556 --> 01:12:33.808
In the last 20, 25 years, that's changed.

01:12:33.891 --> 01:12:39.063
Now about 70% of biomedical research
is funded by industry.

01:12:39.647 --> 01:12:41.315
They're paying for the research,

01:12:41.399 --> 01:12:45.570
so naturally we're going to get
the results that they want to share.

01:12:45.653 --> 01:12:50.575
So devices can be on the market for years
and cause many deaths, many injuries

01:12:50.658 --> 01:12:52.493
before it becomes public.

01:12:52.577 --> 01:12:55.204
<i>A medical device
implanted in thousands of people</i>

01:12:55.288 --> 01:12:57.665
<i>that is linked
to more than two dozen deaths...</i>

01:12:57.748 --> 01:12:59.834
<i>During emergency open-heart surgery,</i>

01:12:59.917 --> 01:13:02.670
<i>doctors removed
this one-inch piece of metal.</i>

01:13:02.753 --> 01:13:04.422
<i>It floated in front of our eyes,</i>

01:13:04.505 --> 01:13:08.718
<i>literally, first into the right atrium
and then into the right ventricle.</i>

01:13:08.801 --> 01:13:11.679
<i>Major health concern over breast implants.</i>

01:13:11.762 --> 01:13:15.057
<i>They could cause a rare form of cancer.</i>

01:13:15.141 --> 01:13:16.851
<i>It may cause other illnesses too.</i>

01:13:16.934 --> 01:13:19.937
<i>When she had hers taken out,
they found mold inside,</i>

01:13:20.021 --> 01:13:21.272
<i>and she's not alone.</i>

01:13:21.355 --> 01:13:25.943
<i>Two dead, 179 exposed
to a dangerous superbug.</i>

01:13:26.027 --> 01:13:28.362
<i>A piece of medical equipment
may be to blame.</i>

01:13:28.446 --> 01:13:32.366
<i>A device called a morcellator
as used to shred fibroid tumors.</i>

01:13:32.450 --> 01:13:34.076
<i>so they could be easily removed.</i>

01:13:34.160 --> 01:13:37.788
<i>The shredding ended up
inadvertently spreading the cancer.</i>

01:13:37.872 --> 01:13:40.082
<i>A defibrillator was withdrawn
from the market</i>

01:13:40.166 --> 01:13:43.210
<i>after 13 deaths
were linked to wiring problems.</i>

01:13:43.294 --> 01:13:47.214
<i>The FDA approved this device,
but did not require testing in humans.</i>

01:13:47.298 --> 01:13:50.051
<i>We can no longer rely
on the medical device companies</i>

01:13:50.134 --> 01:13:52.887
<i>to do what's in the best interest
of the patient.</i>

01:13:53.596 --> 01:13:56.515
<i>And we can no longer rely on the FDA</i>

01:13:56.599 --> 01:13:59.143
<i>to properly regulate these devices.</i>

01:14:00.227 --> 01:14:05.358
I was at the Food and Drug
Administration from 2006 to 2009.

01:14:05.900 --> 01:14:09.070
I was the lead gastroenterologist
of devices.

01:14:10.863 --> 01:14:14.200
I think I cleared,
or was involved in the clearance,

01:14:14.283 --> 01:14:17.119
of over 250-odd devices

01:14:17.870 --> 01:14:20.581
I think the vast majority of doctors

01:14:20.665 --> 01:14:22.667
and scientists at the FDA...

01:14:23.334 --> 01:14:26.420
do their best.
They do it with integrity, honesty.

01:14:27.254 --> 01:14:32.593
In mid-2009, a file came on my desk
to look at this CT scanner,

01:14:32.677 --> 01:14:37.098
this device that affects
many millions of people in our country.

01:14:37.723 --> 01:14:42.061
A CT scan takes the equivalent
of hundreds and hundreds of X-rays.

01:14:42.144 --> 01:14:44.480
while a machine rotates around your body.

01:14:44.563 --> 01:14:49.276
They're an incredibly good test
for diagnosing a range of diseases

01:14:49.360 --> 01:14:52.863
that gives you
very sophisticated 3-D images.

01:14:53.364 --> 01:14:57.535
But the doses of radiation
that we use day in and day out for CT

01:14:57.618 --> 01:15:00.955
are in the range that we know
it will cause cancer in some people.

01:15:01.414 --> 01:15:05.292
And yet, the use of CT scanning
has quadrupled in the last 15 years.

01:15:12.258 --> 01:15:13.843
The elephant in the room

01:15:13.926 --> 01:15:16.846
is it's a very profitable
part of the health care system.

01:15:16.929 --> 01:15:20.683
It's a way a lot of radiologists,
emergency departments, hospitals

01:15:20.766 --> 01:15:21.600
make money

01:15:22.143 --> 01:15:24.645
There's a lot of excess use
of this device,

01:15:24.729 --> 01:15:30.192
and so I simply said,
"We should have a warning on the FDA label

01:15:30.276 --> 01:15:31.652
just to warn the doctor...

01:15:32.319 --> 01:15:36.282
and therefore the patient,
that actually if you use this device...

01:15:37.366 --> 01:15:39.535
and certainly if you use it repeatedly...

01:15:40.244 --> 01:15:41.996
your risk of cancer

01:15:42.079 --> 01:15:45.249
or developing
abdominal cancer will increase.

01:15:45.708 --> 01:15:48.377
I couldn't believe the pushback I'd got

01:15:48.753 --> 01:15:51.464
from managers with no medical experience.

01:15:52.048 --> 01:15:55.092
There was a group of FDA physicians

01:15:55.176 --> 01:15:59.513
who were very concerned about the way
products were being cleared and approved.

01:16:00.097 --> 01:16:02.183
We took these concerns

01:16:02.266 --> 01:16:05.269
up the chain of command to Jeffrey Shuren,

01:16:05.352 --> 01:16:09.023
the director
of the Center for Medical Devices at FDA.

01:16:09.732 --> 01:16:11.400
And what did he do?

01:16:11.484 --> 01:16:14.487
He not only did nothing,
he took it one step further.

01:16:15.112 --> 01:16:17.073
He retaliated against people.

01:16:18.074 --> 01:16:20.201
Once we started complaining...

01:16:20.910 --> 01:16:25.915
FDA put their spy software
in our computers.

01:16:27.124 --> 01:16:31.378
And they were monitoring
all our activities.

01:16:31.796 --> 01:16:35.925
The FDA installed
what's called Spector software

01:16:36.008 --> 01:16:40.096
onto a number of physicians'
and scientists' computers,

01:16:40.513 --> 01:16:44.850
and it allowed them to capture screenshots
every two seconds...

01:16:45.267 --> 01:16:46.560
and keystrokes.

01:16:47.103 --> 01:16:53.484
It's as if to say their own doctors
are somehow criminals for exposing...

01:16:54.944 --> 01:16:57.071
a public health issue.

01:16:58.030 --> 01:17:02.368
It left a tremendous chill
amongst the FDA scientists.

01:17:16.132 --> 01:17:19.385
Listen, safety's as important to us
as it is to anybody else.

01:17:19.468 --> 01:17:23.389
None of us want a product on the market
that's not safe, right?

01:17:23.472 --> 01:17:26.267
That's why we rely on regulators
to help us get there.

01:17:26.350 --> 01:17:28.853
I think the US regulatory system
works well.

01:17:28.936 --> 01:17:31.772
It's robust, it's thorough,
and it's been very effective.

01:17:33.232 --> 01:17:34.358
<i>Ladies and gentlemen,</i>

01:17:34.441 --> 01:17:38.779
<i>please welcome president and CEO
of AdvaMed, Scott Whitaker.</i>

01:17:41.740 --> 01:17:44.451
The device industry
is very well represented

01:17:44.535 --> 01:17:46.662
by their main lobbying group, AdvaMed.

01:17:46.745 --> 01:17:48.372
<i>Good afternoon, everyone,</i>

01:17:48.455 --> 01:17:51.458
<i>and welcome to the Global Summit
for Medical Technology.</i>

01:17:52.334 --> 01:17:54.378
<i>This is a room full of disruptors.</i>

01:17:55.254 --> 01:17:57.673
<i>We are risk-takers of the highest order.</i>

01:17:58.674 --> 01:18:02.678
<i>Not enough Americans understand
the important role we play,</i>

01:18:02.761 --> 01:18:06.432
<i>or frankly give us enough credit
for the innovation we bring.</i>

01:18:07.141 --> 01:18:09.602
<i>Sure, we'll pay attention to Washington.</i>

01:18:09.894 --> 01:18:11.770
<i>That's my job. That's what I do.</i>

01:18:12.438 --> 01:18:16.734
<i>But we have more power in this room
than most governments around the world.</i>

01:18:17.234 --> 01:18:20.112
<i>We have the ability
to create jobs and prosperity...</i>

01:18:20.946 --> 01:18:24.742
<i>to open and expand markets
and unleash innovation.</i>

01:18:25.326 --> 01:18:28.871
<i>Let's show the world that we are
what's next.</i>

01:18:38.339 --> 01:18:39.882
They have lobbied hard

01:18:39.965 --> 01:18:44.678
to see the standards for approval
of devices watered down over the years.

01:18:45.554 --> 01:18:48.766
Device companies
unleash armies of lobbyists

01:18:48.849 --> 01:18:50.893
in order to influence politicians.

01:18:50.976 --> 01:18:54.104
And these politicians are vulnerable.
They don't know science.

01:18:54.188 --> 01:18:57.107
It's often very flowery
and impressive language

01:18:57.191 --> 01:18:59.151
about how they put patients first

01:18:59.235 --> 01:19:01.570
and they want only the best.

01:19:01.654 --> 01:19:05.866
We want to make sure that new
medical innovations get to patients

01:19:05.950 --> 01:19:09.411
and help save lives,
improve the human condition,

01:19:09.495 --> 01:19:12.456
eliminate suffering,
and make this world a better place,

01:19:12.539 --> 01:19:13.999
That's what we all agree on, right?

01:19:14.708 --> 01:19:16.168
The medical device industry

01:19:16.252 --> 01:19:18.712
has incredible levels of influence
in Washington, D.C.

01:19:18.796 --> 01:19:21.048
They have provided dark money
contributions

01:19:21.131 --> 01:19:24.301
that are used to secretly fund
political campaigns.

01:19:24.385 --> 01:19:28.555
Medical device companies also fund
think tanks and patient advocacy groups

01:19:28.639 --> 01:19:30.808
that can go to Congress
and make the case for them.

01:19:32.017 --> 01:19:34.770
Perhaps an even worse problem
is the revolving door.

01:19:34.853 --> 01:19:39.358
A number of FDA officials
have both come from industry

01:19:39.441 --> 01:19:42.194
and then go back to industry
after they're at FDA.

01:19:42.987 --> 01:19:44.947
When they go to work for the companies,

01:19:45.030 --> 01:19:47.199
they can tell the companies all the tricks

01:19:47.283 --> 01:19:51.245
of how to get around FDA regulations,
how to get what you want.

01:19:51.954 --> 01:19:55.374
Almost all the heads at the FDA
went on to work for industry.

01:20:36.957 --> 01:20:39.418
<i>President Donald Trump
says he's picked a nominee</i>

01:20:39.501 --> 01:20:41.503
<i>to run the Food and Drug Administration.</i>

01:20:41.587 --> 01:20:45.591
<i>Dr. Scott Gottlieb is a popular choice
in the pharmaceutical industry.</i>

01:20:45.674 --> 01:20:48.802
<i>"Thank God it's Gottlieb," said
an investment analyst at Robert Baird.</i>

01:20:48.886 --> 01:20:50.596
<i>Why would they have that reaction?</i>

01:20:50.679 --> 01:20:54.933
<i>They were breathing a sigh of relief.
He's a known entity in the industry.</i>

01:20:55.017 --> 01:20:56.894
I've known Scott
for a long time.

01:20:56.977 --> 01:20:57.811
He took that job

01:20:57.895 --> 01:21:01.565
because he wants to do what's in the best
interest of the American people

01:21:02.024 --> 01:21:05.027
and the agency, and not what's
in the best interest of anyone else.

01:21:06.528 --> 01:21:10.783
Gottlieb has been a consultant
to a range of medical industries.

01:21:10.866 --> 01:21:13.077
He's also worked
at a venture capital firm

01:21:13.160 --> 01:21:17.623
that actually specializes in investing
in start-up medical device companies.

01:21:18.248 --> 01:21:20.876
<i>I'm proud of my relationship
with New Enterprise Associates.</i>

01:21:20.959 --> 01:21:23.462
<i>It's been one of the premier
venture capital firms in the country,</i>

01:21:23.545 --> 01:21:25.255
<i>starting a lot of innovative ventures.</i>

01:21:25.339 --> 01:21:28.842
<i>Over the time that I was there,
they invested about $14 billion</i>

01:21:28.926 --> 01:21:30.469
<i>in 500 different companies.</i>

01:21:36.392 --> 01:21:39.144
<i>You have spent
your life entrenched in the companies</i>

01:21:39.228 --> 01:21:42.356
<i>that would benefit
from looser regulations.</i>

01:21:42.439 --> 01:21:44.858
<i>But I think it raises
the very real question</i>

01:21:44.942 --> 01:21:50.572
<i>of whether someone who seems to oppose
the FDA's basic safety mission</i>

01:21:50.656 --> 01:21:52.533
<i>should be running the agency.</i>

01:22:03.919 --> 01:22:07.131
I can tell you he doesn't have any bias
as a result of that.

01:22:07.214 --> 01:22:09.842
I've never seen it
and don't expect to see it,

01:22:09.925 --> 01:22:11.802
knowing him the way I do.

01:22:25.566 --> 01:22:28.444
The FDA is supposed to protect
the public interest.

01:22:28.527 --> 01:22:33.115
Unfortunately, their behavior shows
that they have been captured by industry.

01:22:33.198 --> 01:22:35.534
<i>Scott, thank you for coming
across the country</i>

01:22:35.617 --> 01:22:37.661
<i>to participate with us at this conference.</i>

01:22:38.245 --> 01:22:40.080
<i>I speak, I think, for the entire industry.</i>

01:22:40.164 --> 01:22:42.249
<i>Where we were five years ago at the FDA</i>

01:22:42.332 --> 01:22:44.751
<i>compared to where we are today
is night and day.</i>

01:22:44.835 --> 01:22:47.880
<i>And I think your leadership
has made a huge difference</i>

01:22:47.963 --> 01:22:49.882
<i>and we are really grateful for that.</i>

01:22:53.010 --> 01:22:57.014
In 25 years,
we will, I think, be worse off.

01:22:57.097 --> 01:23:00.517
All the legislation we're seeing,
again, driven by lobbying from industry,

01:23:00.601 --> 01:23:01.727
is moving in the wrong direction

01:23:01.977 --> 01:23:04.938
and there's no evidence
that's gonna shift.

01:23:06.023 --> 01:23:09.610
<i>I just came out of a briefing
with senior officials at the White House</i>

01:23:09.693 --> 01:23:13.614
<i>about the executive order that
President Trump will sign this morning.</i>

01:23:13.697 --> 01:23:15.741
We issued an order which says,

01:23:15.824 --> 01:23:20.954
for every one new regulation,
two old regulations must be eliminated.

01:23:22.331 --> 01:23:25.417
"Regulation is bad. Let's cut regulations.

01:23:25.501 --> 01:23:29.004
For every regulation,
we're going to cut umpteen regulations."

01:23:29.087 --> 01:23:30.297
That bravado...

01:23:31.048 --> 01:23:33.050
may apply to certain fields,

01:23:33.133 --> 01:23:36.553
but it can't and shouldn't apply

01:23:36.637 --> 01:23:40.516
when you're talking about
putting a device in someone's body.

01:23:45.437 --> 01:23:47.022
<i>We're very proud of this one.</i>

